         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">8/2/83 ¶  ¶ This day, dear Sir Joseph, I was greatly pleased to receive the finishing part of the third volume of your important "Flora of British India," ¶  the value of which cannot be overrated. ¶ ...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">83.02.08</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To Joseph Hooker</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">RBG Kew, Kew correspondence, Australia, Mueller, 1882-90, ff. 50-1.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">8/2/83</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>This day, dear Sir Joseph, I was greatly pleased to receive the finishing part of the third volume of your important "Flora of British India,"<note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>J. Hooker (1875-97).</p>
               </note> the value of which cannot be overrated.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>In casting a glance on the pages I notice, that you maintain the name <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">Lysimachia</hi>
               </seg>
               <seg style="font-style: italic; "> </seg>
               <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">Javanica</hi>
               </seg>. Allow me, to draw your attention to the appendix, written by me for Campbell's New Hebrides in 1873.<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>B73.07.02.</p>
               </note> Receiving <name key="Lysimachia%20decurrens">Lysimachia decurrens</name> from Java then, therefore from the very place, where the Forsters obtained their plant, I enquired into the synonymy, and was able from authentic specimens to refer L. Javanica, L. multiflora and L. Sinica <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>to L. decurrens. This I mentioned to Dr Hance at the time, who received also "Campbell's New Hebrides," and hence it was, that he distributed the plant under its oldest name. An insignificant publication, such as my contribution to the little work above named, is so easily overlooked, that it is not surprising, that you missed the reference to the first name.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>An other item of some interest to you for the <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">genera</hi>
               </seg>
               <note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Bentham &amp; Hooker (1862-83).</p>
               </note> will be, that Helmholtzia is likely endemic Australian only. I have just received from M. de la Camera<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">i.e. de la Camara.</p>
               </note> the H. glaberrima, who found it on the summit of the White-cap Mountain near the Tweed-River.<note xml:id="ftn5" type="footnote" n="5">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Night-cap Range, NSW?</p>
               </note> I send a short note now on this subject to Caruel for his giornale<note xml:id="ftn6" type="footnote" n="6">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>B83.04.02.</p>
               </note> as he is interested in this plant.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I mentioned to you, so soon as I got the plate 6056 of the Bot. Magazine,<note xml:id="ftn7" type="footnote" n="7">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Philydrum glaberrimum</seg>, illustrated in J. <seg style="">Hooker (1865-1904),</seg> vol. 99, t. 6056 (published 1 September 1873).</p>
               </note> that the plant belonged to the genus Helmholtzia, as defined in 1866,<note xml:id="ftn8" type="footnote" n="8">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>M erected <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Helmholtzia</seg> (<seg style="font-style: italic; ">H. acorifolia</seg>) in B66.12.04, pp. 202-3.</p>
               </note> and that it may be a glabrous form of H. acorifolia.<note xml:id="ftn9" type="footnote" n="9">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>M to J. Hooker, 1 December 1873 (in this edition as 73-12-01b).</p>
               </note> In reply you wrote, that you had asked Prof. Oliver, to see, whether the plant occurred in the "fragmenta," but that he had missed to note it;<note xml:id="ftn10" type="footnote" n="10">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Letter not found.</p>
               </note> my Census<note xml:id="ftn11" type="footnote" n="11">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>B82.03.04.</p>
               </note> will facilitate all references to that work in future.</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">Regardfully your</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Ferd. von Mueller.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
